  <p xml:id="auto_a8elc1pw">
      <m>\textbf{ Key Takeaway}</m>
  </p>
  <p xml:id="auto_3h0ww8ui">
    <alert>Vector notation </alert> is a way of representing quanties that have both magnitude and direction in mathematics. 
    In <xref ref="vect-notation-1"/> below, we can represent a vector from a point <m>A</m> to 
    point <m>B</m> as <m>\overrightarrow{\textbf{AB}} = \mathbf{a} = \underset{\sim}{\mathbf{a}}</m>
  </p>
  <!-- <p xml:id="auto_8m1mqrjk">
    As well represent a vector from point <m>B</m> to point <m>B</m> we can represent it
      <m>\overrightarrow{BA} = \mathbf{-a} = -\underset{\sim}{\mathbf{a}}</m>
  </p> -->
  <figure xml:id="vect-notation-1">
    <caption></caption>
    <image width="60%">
      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
          \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
          \coordinate (B) at (6,0);
          \node[left] at (A) {A};
          \node[right] at (B) {B};
          \draw[thick] (A) -- (B);
          \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (A) -- (3,0);
          \node[above] at (3,0) { $\mathbf{a}$ or $\underset{\sim}{\mathbf{a}}$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
  </figure>
  <p xml:id="auto_13gepgf2">
    Similarly, if the direction of the vector is reversed, from point <m>B</m> to point <m>A</m> 
    the vector is represented as <m>\overrightarrow{BA} = \mathbf{-a} = -\underset{\sim}{\mathbf{a}}</m>
  </p>
    
