    <p>Representation of Vectors and Vector Notation</p>
    <p xml:id="auto_xpb0q66g">
        Since <alert>vectors</alert> describe both <alert>magnitude</alert> and <alert>direction</alert>, we cannot represent them using simple numbers alone. 
        To communicate mathematical ideas clearly, we need a standardized way to draw and write vectors so that everyone interprets them in exactly the same way. 
        The following activity will help you explore how to visualize and record these movements before we define the formal notation.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="auto_3mtyngyv">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_0k0vf2ay">
            <p xml:id="auto_jha05k4v">
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task xml:id="auto_nhmfbe3z">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_ljr17b1q">
                    Go into the school compound field, choose a starting point and mark it as point <m>\text{A}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_t05aztat">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_qbcvg8a2">
                    Standing at point <m>\text{A}</m>, locate the <alert>north</alert>, <alert>south</alert>, <alert>west</alert>, and <alert>east</alert> directions.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_bystwt8k">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_e2hzqwgf">
                    From point <m>\text{A}</m>, walk <m>20</m> steps to the <alert>north</alert> direction and mark it as point <m>\text{B}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_blbb4b7b">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_4moumk26">
                    From point <m>\text{B}</m>, walk <m>15</m> steps to the <alert>east</alert> direction and mark it as point <m>\text{C}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_irxrrsc0">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_54oubh5b">
                    On a piece of graph paper, draw a sketch that shows your path from point <m>\text{A}</m> to <m>\text{B}</m> and then from <m>\text{B}</m> to <m>\text{C}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_bidefu74">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_8o0yb55n">
                    Think of a way on how you can represent the movement from point <m>\text{A}</m> to <m>\text{B}</m> using notation, also from point <m>\text{B}</m> to <m>\text{C}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_wlj0a5ms">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_fr7rt4m4">
                    Suppose you now move in a reverse way from point <m>\text{C}</m> to point <m>\text{A}</m> following the same path. How would you represent that movement using notation?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="auto_h8m34yhb">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_iouk91d2">
                    Discuss your ideas and representations with the rest of the learners in class.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <insight xml:id="auto_vnhu46oj">
        <p xml:id="auto_cdhwlv4x">
            We can represent a vector by a line drawn between two points 
            as shown in <xref ref="repsentation-vec-1"/> below:
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="repsentation-vec-1">
            <caption></caption>
            <image width="60%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                        % Draw an arrow from A to B
                        \draw[|-|] (0,0) -- (4,0) node[right] {Q};
                        
                        % Label points
                        \node[left] at (0,0) {P};
                        
                        % Draw vector
                        \draw [-{Latex[scale=1.5]}] (2,0) -- (2.1,0); 
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <!-- <p xml:id="auto_vq24yyqd">
            In <xref ref="repsentation-vec-1"/>, the direction of
            the vector is indicated by an arrow pointing to the right, while
            its magnitude is determined by the length of <m>PQ</m>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_kic9bpeg">
            We use <alert>vector notation</alert> to represent a vector between two points.
            Vector <m>\text{PQ}</m> can be written as <m>\underset{\sim}{\text{PQ}}</m> or <m>\overrightarrow{\text{PQ}}</m> or <m>\textbf{PQ}</m>.
        </p> -->
        <!-- <p xml:id="auto_ev55cqjw">
            A vector <m>PQ</m> can be denoted as <m>\underset{\sim}{PQ}</m> or <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m>.The magnitude of vector <m>PQ</m>
            is represented as <m>|PQ|</m>. In this case, we refer to <m>P</m> as <alert>initial point</alert> and <m>Q</m>
            as the <alert>terminal point</alert>
        </p> -->
        <!-- <p xml:id="auto_m956s6y5">
            Additionally, a vector can also be represented using a single small letter,such as  <m>\mathbf{a}</m> or <m>\underset{\sim}{\mathbf{a}}</m>.
        </p> -->
        <p xml:id="auto_72xb1gg2">
            <alert>Vector notation </alert> is a way of representing quanties that have both magnitude and direction. 
            Vector <m>\textbf{PQ}</m> can be denoted as <m>\underset{\sim}{PQ}</m> or <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> or <m>\mathbf{PQ}</m>.The magnitude of vector <m>\textbf{PQ}</m>
            is represented as <m>|\textbf{PQ}|</m>. In this case, we refer to <m>P</m> as <alert>initial point</alert> and <m>Q</m>
            as the <alert>terminal point</alert>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_5cub7uz2">
            Additionally, a vector can also be represented using a single small letter,such as  <m>\mathbf{a}</m> or <m>\underset{\sim}{\mathbf{a}}</m>.
            In <xref ref="vect-notation-11"/> below, we can represent a vector from a point <m>\text{P}</m> to 
            point <m>Q</m> as <m>\overrightarrow{PQ} = \mathbf{a} = \underset{\sim}{\mathbf{a}}</m>
    </p>
    <!-- <p xml:id="auto_myjx0c6m">
        As well represent a vector from point <m>B</m> to point <m>B</m> we can represent it
        <m>\overrightarrow{BA} = \mathbf{-a} = -\underset{\sim}{\mathbf{a}}</m>
    </p> -->
    <figure xml:id="vect-notation-11">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="60%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
            \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
            \coordinate (B) at (6,0);
            \node[left] at (A) {P};
            \node[right] at (B) {Q};
            \draw[thick] (A) -- (B);
            \draw[-{Latex[length=3mm]}] (A) -- (3,0);
            \node[above] at (3,0) { $\mathbf{a}$ or $\underset{\sim}{\mathbf{a}}$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p xml:id="auto_m7wendmv">
        Similarly, if the direction of the vector is reversed, from point <m>\text{Q}</m> to point <m>\text{P}</m> 
        the vector is represented as <m>\overrightarrow{QP} = \mathbf{-a} = -\underset{\sim}{\mathbf{a}}</m>
    </p>  
  </insight>

